==English==
===Etymology===
Middle English

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-æk|-æk]]

====Noun====
'''rack'''
# a series of one or more [[shelf|shelves]], stacked one above the other
# a series of [[gear]]s arranged in a straight line on flat plain
# a frame with which to hang various items.
# a device used to torture victims by stretching them beyond their natural limits.
# a pair of [[antler]]s (as on deer, moose or elk).
# a cut of [[meat]] involving several adjacent [[rib]]s
#: ''rack of lamb''
# (''slang'') a woman's breasts.
::Synonyms - see [[WikiSaurus:breasts]]

====Translations====
*Dutch: [[rek]] (1), [[pijnbank]] (2)
*Finnish: [[räkki]] (1), [[teline]] (1), [[piinapenkki]] (2)

===Etymology===
From the noun ''rack''
====Verb====
'''rack'''

# to place in or hang on a rack

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[reċċan]]''
====Verb====
'''rack'''

# [[stretch]] joints of a person
# inflict [[torture]], pain
# (slang) to "rack" or strike a person, (usually a male, and usually using an object as a weapon to do the action) in the testicles, or "balls," causing extreme pain. This can be done for safety, but is usually done for crude fun.

